Perspectives on Sino-American Relations 2019
NEW YORK – In 2018, the new and increasingly unpredictable dynamics of Sino-American relations have unsettled large parts of Asia.
One year ago, US President Donald Trump returned from his particularly grandiose "State Visit Plus" from Beijing, from which China had hoped that Trump's anti-China campaign rhetoric would finally belong to the past.
Twelve months later, China and the United States are entangled in a trade war, and the Trump administration has replaced the US "strategic engagement" in China with "strategic competition."
In addition, the US, European, and Chinese economies and markets were booming a year ago.
Today, there is widespread uncertainty in the financial markets, growth is slowing down in China and Europe, and in America, higher interest rates are beginning to take effect.
The uncertainty regarding the future development of nuclear negotiations with North Korea also clouds the picture.
What, then, are the prospects for the relations between the USA and China in 2019?
It is likely that an agreement on reducing the bilateral trade deficit and on the import decisions China will make in this regard will be reached by March.
An agreement on lowering tariffs is also possible by then, although the complexity of the issue could extend the targeted timeframe.
If tariffs were negotiated one by one, it could take a year to get anywhere.
Should Chinese economic reformers instead choose a more drastic approach, by gradually committing themselves to the abolition of all tariffs over time and urging Americans to do the same, a faster result could be achieved.
This, however, would run counter to the interests of Chinese trade officials, who have been trained for decades to give little, let alone everything at once.
The reform of so-called forced technology transfer should be relatively straightforward.
Nevertheless, a reform is one thing, while the way in which contractual agreements might be interpreted in practice is another, even if there are no specific provisions regarding technology transfer.
Protection of intellectual property is, however, extremely problematic.
Previous agreements made under the government of President Barack Obama could be reaffirmed.
Their enforcement or judicial action against violations of intellectual property rights remains, however, a hopeless endeavor.
A possible mechanism would be to subject relevant contracts between Chinese and foreign companies to international commercial arbitration tribunals based in Singapore or Switzerland, which are specifically tasked with enforcing the protection of intellectual property.
Should China raise objections, it could develop its own international commercial arbitration process based in China.
In order to strengthen its international credibility, it would have to appoint qualified foreigners to its arbitration body.
No one has trust in Chinese commercial courts.
For its own domestic reform needs, China must move towards completely independent commercial and civil chambers within its judicial system, even though the criminal chamber continues to be subject to political control.
American concerns regarding state subsidies within the framework of the country's "Made in China 2025" strategy will be difficult to resolve.
The fact is that all countries provide some degree of state support to their domestic technology sectors, although this is highest in China.
Even if we were to prescribe a maximum level of state support for a particular company, compliance would be difficult to assess.
I am not confident that a negotiation result will be achieved in this area.
Perhaps America simply has to outcompete China by increasing public investments in research and development in the fields of information technology and biotechnology.
We should also not rule out the possibility that China offers tariff reforms to the rest of the international community.
This could lead China, over time, to decide on the drastic step of agreeing to duty-free trade not only with the USA, but with all member states of the World Trade Organization.
In this way, China would be presented with an almost irresistible opportunity to position itself as a champion of global free trade and to curb the trend towards protectionism.
In the course of such a change, China could ask the member states of the Trans-Pacific Partnership (TPP) to join, in order to surpass the USA (which withdrew from the free trade agreement as one of the first official actions of Trump) in the Asia-Pacific region.
China can be remarkably nimble when it detects a political breach and market opening.
The negotiations would be difficult, but Japan's reservations about China's accession to the TPP have decreased since the recent visit of Prime Minister Shinzo Abe to Beijing.
Given the central strategic challenges in its relationship with the USA, China is likely to seek to reduce conflicts in its relations with other countries in the general foreign and security policy in 2019.
In relations with Japan, there is already a certain normalization.
Recent data from the Japanese Coast Guard indicate a significant reduction in Chinese incursions into the area of the Senkaku/Diaoyu Islands in the East China Sea.
China also wants to ease tensions with the Association of Southeast Asian Nations over the South China Sea through the accelerated negotiation of a "Code of Conduct".
Moreover, China is likely to have a more relaxed relationship with India after the bilateral summit in Wuhan in April.
And China could begin to moderate its stance towards Taiwan, given the electoral defeat suffered by the Democratic Progressive Party, which supports independence, in the local and regional elections last month by Taiwanese President Tsai Ing-wen.
This would naturally change radically if the USA continues with further significant arms sales to Taiwan, which is likely.
Incidents at sea with the USA in the South China Sea continue to occur, and the conflict could escalate if the USA more forcefully emphasizes its stance on "freedom of navigation" next year.
Across all of Eurasia, China will continue to implement its major project "New Silk Road."
In recent months, however, the initiative in China has caused less political controversy.
Among Chinese officials, there are already discussions about revising certain modalities, following Sri Lanka's handover of the Hambantota Port to China, which triggered negative reactions and raised concerns regarding the long-term financiability of the New Silk Road.
2019 could see fewer triumphal announcements regarding the New Silk Road.
Furthermore, China is likely to consolidate and expand its role within the United Nations and existing Bretton Woods institutions, rather than highlighting new institutions of international political action.
It will probably continue to appear as a new advocate for the WHO and maintain its stance on global climate change, as agreed in the 2015 Paris Climate Agreement.
More prudent representatives of the foreign policy establishment in China consider it better to focus on the existing mechanisms of the global rules-based system, especially when the USA consistently show contempt for it.
While China tries to stabilize its relations with the USA and reduce tensions in its relations with other countries, its leadership will likely use the year 2019 to form a well-founded judgment about the future of US policy: The consequences of the Mueller investigation for Trump and his government, and whether a new president in 2020 (or earlier) would change the new US strategy in any way.
Although they have already come to the conclusion that America's stance toward China has undergone profound changes, they are still uncertain about the exact form this change takes and whether a fundamental strategic shift (as opposed to tactical measures) is warranted.
